	<h3 id="comments">8 to &#8220;Twilight, the Anti-Fan, and the Culture Wars&#8221;</h3>

	<div class="navigation">
		<div class="alignleft"></div>
		<div class="alignright"></div>
	</div>
<br class="clear" />
	<ol class="commentlist">
	   <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-32">
   <div id="div-comment-32" class="thechild">
      <div class="leftarea cleft">
         	  </div>
      <div class="rightarea cright">      
      <div class="comment-author vcard by">
         <cite class="fn">Lennard</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>      </div>
      
      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://reviewsindepth.com/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/comment-page-1/#comment-32">April 2, 2010 at 8:50 am</a></div>

      <p>The problem with Twilight is that it is both extremely popular and a whole different affair than Buffy or Stoker&#8217;s Dracula. Buffy is tough. There are men who return to their abusive female spouses, too. Also, Buffy has character and is interesting, she has a personality, she shows initiative. Lastly, Buffy was never as popular as the Twilight series.<br />
Stoker&#8217;s Dracula is immortal and he has a valid reason to stalk women: He drinks their blood. They fall for him, sure, but some men fall for the female vampires, too. I think for a 1800&#8242;s story, it is very evened out in regards to gender affairs.</p>
<p>Twilight, on the other hand, fails to explain why Edward is ever interested in Bella. She is devoid of everything. In one scene in the book, where she is about 80% sure that he is a vampire, she decides to review her math homework. How characterless.<br />
I think Twilight is porn for females in that it shows Bella not giving a shit at all for all the things Edward does in his free time. He listens to classical music, but is this elaborated upon? Does Bella try to understand it&#8217;s appeal to him? He reads books, and with the exception of one, she doesn&#8217;t care either. Edward is painted as a pretty picture from the outside, to look at, mysterious, rebellious, articulate and potent, but is he ever more than an object? Does Bella really care about his character? No, she only cares that he cares about her. As long as he shows interest, she doesn&#8217;t have a reason not to obsess about herself. He is an object, as much as the breasts and genitals of a woman are an object of pornography. </p>
<p>Also it is immensely gay to have the vampires sparkle in sunlight. Twilight is chopping the balls of everything cool in vampire stories and repackaging it, Christian and mainstream friendly.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/?replytocom=32#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-32", "32", "respond", "161")'>Reply</a>      </div>
    </div>
      </div>
   </li>               
<ul class="children">
   <li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-33">
   <div id="div-comment-33" class="thechild">
      <div class="leftarea cleft">
         	  </div>
      <div class="rightarea cright">      
      <div class="comment-author vcard by">
         <cite class="fn">Dan Haggard</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>      </div>
      
      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://reviewsindepth.com/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/comment-page-1/#comment-33">April 2, 2010 at 9:24 am</a></div>

      <p>Hi Lennard -</p>
<p>Thanks for your post.  Your reading is quite interesting.  I agree with quite a lot of what you say.  I don&#8217;t doubt that in some sense twilight fans fantasize about an Edward type character falling in love with them for no reason at all&#8230;  It&#8217;s quite odd that a very old vampire would find any stimulation in a teenage girl.  (but this is often true of vampire fiction &#8211; Buffy is another example in this respect also) This speaks to the point that the story is pretty incoherent even as a piece of fiction, let alone representative parable.</p>
<p>So I don&#8217;t disagree with you on any of that.  I guess I&#8217;m asking what causes us to be so aggressive toward girls that are emotionally satisfied by this kind of story.  What are the psychological motivations that are leading to such extreme hatred of this particular piece of fiction?  </p>
<p>Have you ever read any romance fiction? &#8211; I&#8217;m talking Mills and Boon type stuff.  They employ many different sub plot types &#8211; many of which are just as silly as the twilight plot (some can be considerably more sophisticated).  Make no mistake &#8211; millions of women enjoy these books and not just teenagers.  Should we be campaigning just as hard against these forms of fiction?  They are often frowned upon &#8211; but in a way accepted because they don&#8217;t attempt to push their way into mainstream consciousness.  As long as it stays in its box it is tolerated.</p>
<p>So twilight mainstreamed &#8211; and a threatened and derogatory stance is adopted by many people.  Why?  That&#8217;s the question I really want to get at.  I don&#8217;t want to demonise anti-fans&#8230; or even say they are wrong in their stance&#8230; I want to get to the heart of what it is that motivates the extreme reaction.  I completely agree with you that Twilight is bad&#8230;  But so many other forms of terrible fiction don&#8217;t elicit this response.  So what&#8217;s different here?</p>
<p>My supposition is that people unconsciously adopt the roles suggested in the fiction itself.  But I would love to hear other suggestions.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/?replytocom=33#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-33", "33", "respond", "161")'>Reply</a>      </div>
    </div>
      </div>
   </li>               
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
   <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-42">
   <div id="div-comment-42" class="thechild">
      <div class="leftarea cleft">
         	  </div>
      <div class="rightarea cright">      
      <div class="comment-author vcard by">
         <cite class="fn">james</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>      </div>
      
      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://reviewsindepth.com/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/comment-page-1/#comment-42">April 8, 2010 at 11:02 pm</a></div>

      <p>I think this is one of the best articles on twilight.</p>
<p>I would disagree with the notion that Bella is the object though, it is Edward.   Lennard&#8217;s reply notes that Bella has no deep interest in Edward&#8217;s actual life other than an obsessive attraction to him.   His character has no depth &#8211; the listening to classical music and reading simply hint at a sophistication that is attractive but doesn&#8217;t ask why that is so.  By being in the body of an eternal 17 year old and having apparent but poorly verified sophistication and emotional intensity Edward comes across not as a deep character but as &#8216;the brooding intense one&#8217; from a typical boy-band and much like that stereotype he lacks real sophistication and masculinity.   It is after all a fantasy for inexperienced girls.</p>
<p>Because of this it isn&#8217;t necessary to ask why Edward is attracted to Bella, it is simply an expediency for the purpose of creating the fantasy, for the book to go into the issue of attracted in depth would exclude the majority of readers who would realize that a real Edward wouldn&#8217;t actually notice them.</p>
<p>It does say something worrying about younger women&#8217;s attraction for brooding intensity coupled with rejection and abuse.   Perhaps it is &#8216;natural&#8217; as brooding intensity might once have indicated an emotional and intellectual depth and sense of purpose whereas all too often now it is simply a deliberate ruse or a maladjustment with no real depth or purpose.</p>
<p>The anti fan nastiness is in part simply a clubbing together of groups as you&#8217;ve described but I also suspect it is a frustration along the lines of saying &#8220;don&#8217;t you realize it&#8217;s all a lie&#8221; not just as in fiction but the very notion of Edward &amp; Bella&#8217;s attraction and relationship.  I&#8217;m not saying the anti-fans are being sophisticated about it but perhaps sense a phoniness and are disappointed at the willing credulity displayed by fans.   Another aspect, also hit upon by Lennard, is that the &#8216;boy-band&#8217; vampires are really are awful compared to the Bram Stoker vampire, so obviously manipulated to appeal to girls along the same lines as various celebrity images.</p>
<p>Also, part of teen culture seems to be about appearing unenthusiastic about anything, presumably in the hope of looking experienced and therefore of higher social status, it is also a rejection of the innocent enthusiasm of childhood.   The exuberance of fans doesn&#8217;t fit this norm and so the trait is rejected by many younger anti fans.</p>
<p>One final aspect, I suspect that male teens make up a significant proportion of anti fans while female teens make up the overwhelming majority of fans.   Male teens may see the enthusiasm for Edward (or Jacob) as a rejection of them and this might hurt their self esteem so this may come out as anti fan nastiness.   the female anti fans may also be displeased in the sense of thinking of females fans as having &#8216;let the side down&#8217; by falling for something so &#8216;obvious&#8217;</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/?replytocom=42#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-42", "42", "respond", "161")'>Reply</a>      </div>
    </div>
      </div>
   </li>               
