         <cite class="fn"><a href="http://launch.groups.yahoo.com/group/REOFANS/" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-commentauthor','http://launch.groups.yahoo.com']);"  rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Susanna</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>      </div>
      
      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://reviewsindepth.com/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/comment-page-1/#comment-1338">August 18, 2011 at 9:28 pm</a></div>

      <p>I am really interested in what motivates the anti-fan, but mainly because I stumbled on a forum full of them, in a completely different context.  This particular forum has been around 12 years and has 29,800 posts.  It bills itself as a fan club, but it&#8217;s actually an anti-fan club for people who hate REO Speedwagon.  Before reading your article I was thinking that anti-fandom has certain natural advantages, independent of topic.  People expressing hatred need not expose much of themselves, it&#8217;s very safe, and tends to make one feel superior.  There is the usual enjoyment of personal expression, and friendship between people who share a common view, but that works for positive emotions just as much as negative.  The leading anti-fan in this forum I mention, has a particular hatred for Kevin Cronin.  I am guessing that he&#8217;s offended by Kevin&#8217;s high voice, tight pants, heavy jewelry, and slender build.  Kevin looks gay, but is straight, and this particular anti-fan is actually a gay man in the closet.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/?replytocom=1338#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-1338", "1338", "respond", "161")'>Reply</a>      </div>
    </div>
      </div>
   </li>               
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
   <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-2618">
   <div id="div-comment-2618" class="thechild">
      <div class="leftarea cleft">
         	  </div>
      <div class="rightarea cright">      
      <div class="comment-author vcard by">
         <cite class="fn"><a href="http://aruelle.livejournal.com" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-commentauthor','http://aruelle.livejournal.com']);"  rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Aruelle</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>      </div>
      
      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://reviewsindepth.com/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/comment-page-1/#comment-2618">April 8, 2013 at 3:20 am</a></div>

      <p>This is a very interesting article, though I must say that the author appears to have confused Bram Stoker&#8217;s &#8220;Dracula&#8221; (the book) with &#8220;Bram Stoker&#8217;s Dracula&#8221; (the Francis Ford Coppola movie). It is the movie, not the book, where Mina abandons her husband and friends in favour of (mourning) Dracula. The book sees her play an important part in defeating the vampire, after which she goes home with her husband and friends, and later gives birth to a son, in a standard end to vampire stories of the era. I would suggest that at least part of the Twilight hate springs from the public realisation that the vampire has transformed from villain to be vanquished into the hero himself.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/?replytocom=2618#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-2618", "2618", "respond", "161")'>Reply</a>      </div>
    </div>
      </div>
   </li>               
<ul class="children">
   <li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="comment-2619">
   <div id="div-comment-2619" class="thechild">
      <div class="leftarea cleft">
         	  </div>
      <div class="rightarea cright">      
      <div class="comment-author vcard by">
         <cite class="fn"><a href="http://reviewsindepth.com"   rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Dan Haggard</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>      </div>
      
      <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://reviewsindepth.com/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/comment-page-1/#comment-2619">April 8, 2013 at 4:03 am</a></div>

      <p>Hi Aruelle,</p>
<p>Yes you&#8217;re quite right I was actually thinking about the movie rather than the novel &#8211; which was careless of me and I appreciate you pointing it out.  The love affair between Mina and Dracula doesn&#8217;t happen at all in the book.  Having said that &#8211; the convention of the feminine betrayal of the established patriarchy is still there &#8211; it&#8217;s just that the betrayal is suggestive as being more involuntary.  It&#8217;s a not a true betrayal in the sense that their conscious selves are not making the choice.  This would have caused less cognitive dissonance in victorian readers not used to having to identify with a bad guy.  Modern audiences are more willing in this regard.</p>
<p>In any case &#8211; the Coppola movie pre-dates Twilight by quite some time showing that the convention had already established itself in the genre long before.</p>

      <div class="reply">
         <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/03/twilight-the-anti-fan-and-the-culture-wars/?replytocom=2619#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-2619", "2619", "respond", "161")'>Reply</a>      </div>
    </div>
      </div>
   </li>               
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	</ol>

